An LLM, or Large Language Model, is the technical name for the AI system that powers conversational interfaces like ChatGPT, Claude, and Gemini. The "large" refers to both the enormous amount of text these systems are trained on—often hundreds of billions of words from books, websites, and other sources—and the massive number of parameters (adjustable settings) they contain, which can number in the hundreds of billions. These models learn statistical patterns in language during their training, enabling them to predict what words should come next in a sequence, which is fundamentally how they generate human-like responses to your questions and prompts.
